atched the rise of a global war on terror. Germ Wars demonstrates that these movements did not occur separately but are instead deeply entwined—new scientific knowledge of microbes makes possible new mechanisms of war. Whether to eliminate disease or create weapons, the work to harness and control germs and the history of these endeavors provide an important opportunity for investigating how biological natures shape modern life. Germ Wars aims to convince students and scholars as well as policymakers and activists that the ways in which bioterrorism has been produced have consequences for how people live in this world of unspecifiable risks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aBiopolitics. 0aBioterrorismzUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aBioterrorismzUnited StatesxPsychological aspects. 7aSCIENCE / Environmental Science (see also Chemistry / Environmental).2bisacsh  aactivism.  aactivist.  aamerica.  aamerican government.  aamerican history.  aamerican.  abiological science.  abiological weapon.  abiologist.  abiology.  abioterrorism.  abiowarfare.  acontemporary.  adangerous.  adisease.  agerm warfare.  agovernment spending.  agovernment.  amicrobes.  amodern world.  apolicymaker.  apolitics.  arevolution.  ascientific.  aunited states government.  aunited states history.  aus government.  aus history.  awarfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029276540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520966147/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles